
Column Name	Assigned dtype	Explanation
loan_amnt	float32	The listed amount of the loan applied for by the borrower. If LendingClub reduces it during approval (credit review), this reflects the final requested/approved amount. Key for sizing risk — larger amounts often correlate with higher default pressure.
funded_amnt	float32	The total amount actually funded/commit by investors for the loan (usually equals loan_amnt unless partially funded, but in accepted data it's typically the same). Useful for comparing requested vs. actual funding.
int_rate	float32	Interest Rate on the loan (as a percentage, e.g., 12.99 for 12.99%). This is set by LendingClub based on grade/sub-grade/risk. One of the strongest predictors of default — higher rates signal higher risk (your heatmap showed 0.21 correlation with default).
annual_inc	float32	The self-reported annual income provided by the borrower during registration/application. Used heavily in DTI calculation and ability-to-repay assessment. Higher income often protects against default (though weak linear correlation in your heatmap).
dti	float32	Debt-to-Income ratio: Borrower's total monthly debt payments (on existing obligations, excluding mortgage and the new LC loan) divided by monthly gross income, ×100 (percentage). Key approval filter — LendingClub caps this around 36–40%; higher values slightly raise default odds (your density plot showed subtle shift).
fico_range_low	float32	The lower boundary of the borrower's FICO score range at loan origination (FICO reported in 5-point ranges, e.g., 700–704 → low=700). Top predictor of default/success — lower values strongly associate with higher default (your boxplot showed ~20–30 point median gap).
fico_range_high	float32	The upper boundary of the same FICO range (e.g., 704 for above). Often used together with low; many analyses just use the low or average (midpoint) since ranges are narrow. Similar importance to low.
delinq_2yrs	int8	The number of times the borrower had been 30+ days past due on payments in the past 2 years (from credit report). Higher values flag recent delinquency risk → worse grade/higher default likelihood.
inq_last_6mths	int8	Number of credit inquiries (hard pulls) in the last 6 months. More inquiries can signal credit-seeking behavior or distress → negative signal for approval/default.
open_acc	int8	Number of open credit lines/accounts in the borrower's credit file. Too few or too many can indicate risk (e.g., thin file or overextended).
pub_rec	int8	Number of derogatory public records (e.g., bankruptcies, tax liens, judgments) on the credit report. Higher = major red flag → often leads to decline or high grade/rate.
revol_util	float32	Revolving credit utilization rate (%): Amount of revolving credit used / total revolving credit limit available. High utilization (>70–80%) hurts FICO and signals risk → moderate correlation with default and int_rate (your heatmap: 0.26 with int_rate, 0.06 with default).
total_pymnt	float32	Total payments received to date (principal + interest + fees). Outcome-related — for completed loans, compare to funded_amnt to derive actual return/loss. Useful for success measurement (e.g., if total_pymnt < funded_amnt → loss).
loan_status	category	Current status of the loan: Fully Paid, Charged Off, Current, Default, Late (16-30 days), Late (31-120 days), etc. Core outcome variable for your project — group into "good" (Fully Paid) vs. "bad" (Charged Off/Default/Late) for default analysis.
grade	category	LC-assigned loan grade: A (best/lowest risk) to G (worst/highest risk). Summary of all risk factors (FICO, DTI, etc.). Usually #1 most important feature for default prediction and approval (your boxplots showed huge step-up in rate and default by grade).
sub_grade	category	More granular grade: A1 (best) to G5 (worst). Provides finer risk buckets within each letter grade. Often used instead of grade for modeling precision.
home_ownership	category	Home ownership status provided by borrower or from credit report: RENT, OWN, MORTGAGE, OTHER, NONE. Slight default differences (e.g., OWN sometimes lower risk).
verification_status	category	Whether income was verified: Verified, Source Verified, Not Verified. "Verified" means LC checked paystubs/W-2s; can influence trust/approval.
purpose	category	Borrower-selected loan purpose/category: debt_consolidation, credit_card, home_improvement, major_purchase, small_business, etc. Certain purposes (e.g., small_business) show higher default rates in your plots.
addr_state	category	The state (two-letter code) provided by the borrower in the application (or from credit file). Useful for geographic trends (e.g., default rates by state/region).
issue_d	string	The month-year the loan was issued/funded (format: MMM-YYYY, e.g., Dec-2015). Critical for time trends — convert to datetime to analyze changes in approval standards, default rates, average amounts/rates over years (your line plots).
earliest_cr_line	string	The month-year the borrower's earliest reported credit line was opened (from credit file, e.g., Jan-2001). Used to calculate credit history length (age of credit). Longer history often better for approval/lower risk.
